diagnoses: Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms
Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS syndrome)
Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS)
1. Stroke This is a medical condition in which poor blood flow to the brain occurs
depriving brain tissue of oxygen and nutrients. Dysarthria is difficulty pronouncing words and speaking clearly
which can be a sign of stroke. Headache is another common symptom
especially if it is severe and sudden. Weakness or paralysis on one side of the body can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


2. Brain tumor A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Dysarthria can occur when a brain tumor affects areas of the brain that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they may be worse in the morning or when lying down. Weakness or paralysis on one side of the body can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


3. Meningitis Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord. Dysarthria can occur when meningitis affects the nerves that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they may be severe and accompanied by fever
and stiff neck. Weakness or paralysis can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


4. Encephalitis Encephalitis is an inflammation of the brain itself. Dysarthria can occur when encephalitis affects areas of the brain that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they may be severe and accompanied by fever
and seizures. Weakness or paralysis can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


5. Subarachnoid hemorrhage A subarachnoid hemorrhage is a type of stroke that occurs when there is bleeding in the space between the brain and the skull. Dysarthria can occur when the hemorrhage affects areas of the brain that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they are often sudden and severe. Weakness or paralysis on one side of the body can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


6. Epidural hematoma An epidural hematoma is a type of head injury in which blood collects between the skull and the dura mater
the membrane that covers the brain. Dysarthria can occur when the hematoma puts pressure on the brain. Headaches are also common

and they may be severe and accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Weakness or paralysis on one side of the body can also occur. 


7. Subdural hematoma A subdural hematoma is a type of head injury in which blood collects between the dura mater and the arachnoid mater
the membrane that covers the brain. Dysarthria can occur when the hematoma puts pressure on the brain. Headaches are also common

and they may be severe and accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Weakness or paralysis on one side of the body can also occur. 


8. Brain abscess A brain abscess is a collection of pus in the brain. Dysarthria can occur when the abscess affects areas of the brain that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they may be severe and accompanied by fever
and seizures. Weakness or paralysis can also occur

along with nausea and vomiting. 


9. Multiple sclerosis Multiple sclerosis is a chronic inflammatory disease that affects the central nervous system. Dysarthria can occur when multiple sclerosis affects areas of the brain that control speech. Headaches are also common
and they may be accompanied by weakness

or tingling in the arms and legs


10. Guillain-Barré syndrome Guillain-Barré syndrome is an autoimmune disorder that affects the peripheral nervous system. Dysarthria can occur when Guillain-Barré syndrome affects the nerves that control speech. Weakness or paralysis in the arms and legs is also common
and it may progress to the point of needing mechanical ventilation. Nausea and vomiting can also occur.
